9> The <a href="javascript:card_browser(242)">Summit of Amon Hen</a>    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Like I said at the top of my deck, some of my card choices may seem a bit odd. But I<br>
assure you, everything has it&#39;s own purpose in this deck, and there are plenty more cards<br>
that would help me, but I either don&#39;t have them, or don&#39;t have room for them. Now... for<br>
my strategy note, I&#39;m going to describe the &#39;purpose&#39; of every card in this deck, so please<br>
read, and you&#39;ll see why in the world I play all those &#39;odd&#39; cards and combos...<br>
~<br>
FREE PEOPLES:<br>
~<br>
Boromir: <br>
I&#39;ve heard it before. &quot;Why don&#39;t you start with Boromir and Merry?!?&quot; One: Buckleberry<br>
Ferry should not be ignored, it&#39;s like free stealth events for all your companions! Two:<br>
Getting my companions out fast is a neccesity with a small fellowship! I&#39;ve discovered<br>
that since I need all the extra Boromirs to heal his hobbit-pumping exertions, only having<br>
to play one Sam is much better for card flow than playing Boromir at the start and having<br>
to put in duplicates of Sam. Three: He makes hobbits more powerful. Four: If that isn&#39;t<br>
reason enough for you, you need to rethink your view of &quot;strategy&quot;...<br>
<br>
Boromir&#39;s &#39;Accesories&#39;:<br>
Blade of Gondor is a must when playing Boromir: It makes him more powerful; He is a<br>
cantidate for dagger strike; He is damage +1; The game text can be a life-saver; Oh,<br>
C&#39;mon, it&#39;s his freakin personal hand weapon!<br>
Armor is simply a good card, &#39;specially with Lurtz&#39;s Battlecry becoming increasingly<br>
popular...<br>
Athelas can heal his exertions, or my hobbits, or get rid of black breath/blade tip/verily I<br>
come.<br>
Sentinels of Numenor: I play it &#39;cause it makes him stronger. Better than Swordarm, he&#39;s<br>
never defender +1, and who knows; maybe he&#39;ll be in a feirce skirmish and the game text<br>
will truly take effect!<br>
<br>
Pippen, HOSI: <br>
Ahh Pippy... he was born to live, he lives to die! All right, the way I see it is he&#39;s just an<br>
athelas and stealth event rolled into one card! You play him to heal (like athelas) then<br>
next turn kill him against the balrog/witch king/cave troll! (like a stealth: he saves your<br>
bigger companions the wounds) Even play a Hobbit Sword on him and use him twice, in<br>
a feirce skirmish! All for the low twilight of... ONE! Well... okay two if you count<br>
moving.<br>
<br>
Hobbit Sword: <br>
I play hobbits. This makes hobbits stronger. Merry gets even more powerful. Is there<br>
something about this you do NOT understand?!?<br>
<br>
Thror&#39;s Map: <br>
My sites can sometime be important. Just in case my opponents play Nelly, Pathfinder, or<br>
even another map!<br>
<br>
PATHS: <br>
Unfortunately this is the only one I have :( Oh how I wish I had more money! You can<br>
probably figure out WHY this is a good card, what with swarms becoming ever popular.<br>
<br>
Intuition & Stealth: <br>
Hey, look if my hobbits don&#39;t fight, they don&#39;t take wounds (and they spare Boromir the<br>
exertions too) they don&#39;t take wounds, they don&#39;t DIE as quickly.<br>
<br>
O E! G!: <br>
Makes Frodo (or on rare occasions, Sam) strength +1, can take off the one ring, and then<br>
someone whom I play alot enjoys those nassssty black riders!<br>
<br>
There and Back: <br>
More strength to the hobbits! Power... Pride... Fame... eventually Disney World! (or<br>
Mordor-World, take your pick!)<br>
~<br>
SHADOW:<br>
~<br>
Archer Commander:<br>
Without their commander, moria archers can be WIMPS! Strength 4? sheesh! Basically:<br>
you can&#8217;t play archery without at least one of these. A third would go nicely for my deck;<br>
actually I&#8217;ve been haggling with someone for another, and I think we may work it out!<br>
But with only two, my advice is keep one in your hand until sometime in the moria<br>
window, when you play out a swarm of archers. With him and strengtheners and<br>
scimitars, and of course their flying sticks, you can do some serious damage!<br>
<br>
Goblin Archer:<br>
Big twilight, bad game text... I hate this guy, and as soon as I get another Moria Archer<br>
Troop he&#8217;s gone, but for now... I need his archery fire<br>
<br>
Moria Archer Troop:<br>
Their game text makes up for their twilight cost. And! They&#8217;re archers (yeah, with that<br>
name, what&#8217;d you expect, eh?)<br>
<br>
Goblin Marksman:<br>
Archers. Not to mention they&#8217;re pretty powerful for a 3 twilight!<br>
<br>
Goblin Bowman:<br>
Archers. Well... they aren&#8217;t  actually that bad when you have an Archer Commander, a<br>
scimitar on &#8216;em, and one of my eight strengtheners!<br>
<br>
Goblin Runner:<br>
More twilight= more orcs= more archery= more wounds... you follow me?<br>
<br>
Scimitar:<br>
More orcish power! You even get to draw a card! Maybe even another archer!<br>
<br>
Host of Thousands:<br>
Ressurect your fallen archers and runners. This can be deadly, since it&#8217;s practically<br>
counted as another orc, and one of your choosing at that! (despite what some ppl think,<br>
this is NOT plral. HOST not hosts.<br>
<br>
Unfamiliar Territory & Drums:<br>
Some of those wimpish archers could use the added strength.<br>
~<br>
ADVENTURE DECK:<br>
~<br>
Hobbiton Woods: Just in case I can&#8217;t get Buckleberry Ferry out.<br>
Buckleberry Ferry: Like free stelth events!!!<br>
Rivendell Terrace: Under rare circumstances when I don&#8217;t get Boromir out at<br>
Buckleberry, I actually get to draw a card for him here!<br>
Great Chasm: A must for archery decks.<br>
The Bridge: Not like there&#8217;s much choice.<br>
Dimrill Dale: Cheaper orcs= more orcs= more archery.<br>
Anduin Confluence: I don&#8217;t really like this site, but it&#8217;s better than skipping the archery<br>
phase or exerting every companion. &#8216;sides, it&#8217;s not like bounder is that important.<br>
Brown Lands: More archery.<br>
The Summit: More cards= more orcs= more wounds.<br>
~<br>
THE ONE RING:<br>
~<br>
I play Isildur&#8217;s bane &#8216;cause the extra vitality is good for this deck. If you don&#8217;t have the<br>
rare ring... don&#8217;t sweat it, it&#8217;s not that important, the common will work fine.<br>
~<br>
A FEW MORE TIPS:<br>
~<br>
1: I can&#8217;t emphasize enough how crucial it is that you don&#8217;t play Boromir until after<br>
Buckleberry ferry!!!<br>
2: Never double-move unless you&#8217;re at a site late in the path and know your archery<br>
won&#8217;t do the trick. This deck wasn&#8217;t made to be a race deck, but will fill the role<br>
sufficiently. Taking things one step at a time is good for this deck.<br>
3: As I&#8217;ve already said, keep archer commander stocked up for the big fight.<br>
4: ALWAYS discard a card in the regroup phase (unless you&#8217;ve only got 1-2 cards in your<br>
hand) because card flow is neccesary.<br>
5: Kill Pippen the very turn you play him, you don&#8217;t want him filling up the twilight pool<br>
every time you move.<br>
6. Trust your cards. Let me clarify; this deck has won many games. Trust that your<br>
archery will do the trick; trust that if it DOESN&#8217;T, you will be able to run the rest of the<br>
way; trust your strategy to pull you through when you need it; and most importantly:<br>
TRUST IN THE FORCE! </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=23678"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=23678" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
